          <h4>Cordelia Stanwood (1865&ndash;1958)</h4>
          <p>
            Maine field naturalist (Ellsworth). Began ornithological work in
            her early 40s after a teaching career and a nervous breakdown.
            Largely self-taught, photographed birds with a glass-plate
            camera. Reported as the first female professional bird
            photographer; 38 of her photographs appeared in Edward Howe
            Forbush's <em>Birds of Massachusetts</em>. Made scientific
            observations on roughly 100 species. Published in
            <em>Bird-Lore</em>, <em>Blue Bird</em>, <em>Nature and
            Culture</em>, and <em>House Beautiful</em>, plus 20 scholarly
            articles in ornithological journals. Most of her substantive
            work was in articles, not books, but the <em>Bird-Lore</em>
            archive at the
            <a
              href="https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer">Biodiversity Heritage Library</a>
            contains her writing. Her home and woodland became Birdsacre
            Sanctuary, opened to the public in 1960, two years after her
            death.
          </p>

          <h4>Althea Sherman (1853&ndash;1943)</h4>
          <p>
            Iowa naturalist (Farmersburg Township, Clayton County).
            Self-taught ornithologist after a teaching career. In 1915 she
            commissioned a 28-foot wooden tower (9 feet square, with an
            internal staircase, doors, and peepholes) specifically for
            observing Chimney Swifts; she collected 18 years of data using
            it, the first complete life-cycle study of the species.
            Published more than 70 articles in scientific and ornithological
            journals. Elected to AOU membership in 1912 (when the AOU had
            only 100 members). Posthumous book <em>Birds of an Iowa
            Dooryard</em> (1952), edited by Fred J. Pierce, limited to
            1,500 copies. Her articles in <em>Bird-Lore</em> and other
            pre-1929 journals are public domain.
          </p>

          <h4>Margaret Morse Nice (1883&ndash;1974)</h4>
          <p>
            Mount Holyoke College (1901&ndash;1906). Conducted foundational
            long-term study of Song Sparrows in Columbus, Ohio, beginning in
            1929 and running approximately eight years. The work focused on
            individual banded birds and recorded territoriality, breeding,
            learning, and song behavior. Published over 250 papers, 7 books,
            and 3,313 reviews across her career. Her major books, <em>Studies
            in the Life History of the Song Sparrow</em> (1937) and <em>The
            Watcher at the Nest</em> (1939), are not yet public domain under
            the 95-year rule (enter PD on January 1, 2033 and January 1, 2035
            respectively). Her pre-1930 articles in <em>Bird-Lore</em> and
            <em>The Auk</em> are public domain and worth pulling for the
            series, available through
            <a
              href="https://sora.unm.edu/"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer">SORA</a> and the
            <a
              href="https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer">Biodiversity Heritage Library</a>.
          </p>

          <h3>Where to look for clean scans</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <a
                href="https://archive.org/"
                target="_blank"
                rel="noopener noreferrer">Internet Archive</a>. The workhorse.
              PDF, EPUB, and plain text. Ad-free, login optional.
            </li>
            <li>
              <a
                href="https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/"
                target="_blank"
                rel="noopener noreferrer">Biodiversity Heritage Library</a>.
              Best for scientific journals and serious ornithological texts.
              Higher-quality scans for science books.
            </li>
            <li>
              <a
                href="https://www.hathitrust.org/"
                target="_blank"
                rel="noopener noreferrer">HathiTrust</a>. Academic-grade scans;
              full download is sometimes restricted to authenticated users at
              member institutions.
            </li>
            <li>
              <a
                href="https://www.gutenberg.org/"
                target="_blank"
                rel="noopener noreferrer">Project Gutenberg</a>. Cleaner
              plain-text and HTML editions of the most-read titles,
              volunteer-proofread.
            </li>
            <li>
              <a
                href="https://sora.unm.edu/"
                target="_blank"
                rel="noopener noreferrer">SORA</a>. Searchable Ornithological
              Research Archive of major North American ornithology journals.
            </li>
            <li>
              <a
                href="https://www.loc.gov/"
                target="_blank"
                rel="noopener noreferrer">Library of Congress</a>. Hosts
              high-quality scans of many titles, including Burroughs's
              <em>Wake-Robin</em> and Chapman's <em>Handbook</em>.
            </li>
          </ul>

